<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910131-0175</DOCNO><DOCID>910131-0175.</DOCID><HL>   Philip Morris Profit   Rose 2% in 4th Period   On Big Tobacco Gains</HL><DATE>01/31/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C6</SO><CO>   MO</CO><IN>TOBACCO PRODUCTS (TOB)EARNINGS (ERN)BEVERAGES (BVG)DISTILLERS AND BREWERS, MAKERS OF ALCOHOLIC BEVERAGES (DST)FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- Philip Morris Cos. posted hefty fourth-quartergains in its core tobacco and food businesses but reported aslim 2% rise in net income because of a large year-earlierone-time gain.   Net income rose to $880 million, or 95 cents a share, from$863 million, or 93 cents a share. The year-earlier quarterincluded a net gain of $152 million, or 16 cents a share,related to a Kraft General Foods restructuring charge and thesale of the company's stake in Rothmans International PLC.Sales rose 30% to $14.22 billion from $10.96 billion.</LP><TEXT>   Except for the company's Miller Brewing Co. unit,operating units, especially international tobacco, turned inrobust results for the quarter.   While operating profit at Miller Brewing fell 54% to $5million, Philip Morris's domestic tobacco business posted a19% gain in profit to $1.2 billion, while volume roseslightly. Profit in the international tobacco business morethan tripled to $242 million from $71 million. Marc Cohen, ananalyst at Sanford C. Bernstein andamp; Co., estimated that unitsales of cigarettes overseas grew more than 20% in thequarter. Unit volume rose 16% in the year to a record 368.1billion units, the company said.   &quot;They're entering 1991 with tremendous momentum,&quot; Mr.Cohen said. &quot;One of the things that is going to captureinvestor imagination is the scope of their internationalopportunity in cigarettes.&quot;   In the company's food business, operating profit grew 28%to $751 million. Roy Burry, an analyst at Kidder Peabody,said, &quot;The tobacco business continues to drive companyprofits, and the food operation is still benefiting fromsynergies from the Kraft General Foods combination and theaddition of Jacob Suchard in the second half of the year.&quot;Philip Morris said that, including Jacob Suchard, unit volumegrew 6.5% during the year.   Philip Morris said it plans $1.7 billion in capitalspending in 1991, up from $1.4 billion in 1990.   Full-year net rose 20% to $3.54 billion, or $3.83 a share,from $2.95 billion, or $3.18 a share, in 1989. Revenue grew16% to $51.17 billion from $44.08 billion.   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,Philip Morris shares closed at $55.75 each, up 87.5 cents.</TEXT></DOC>